node.title: Sydney woman allegedly scammed $1 million from prospective Canberra home buyer
node.alt: A woman with a drink and book speaks to media outside a courthouse
node.description: A 29-year-old Sydney woman faces court over an alleged property scam that fleeced $1 million from a Canberra woman.
node.content:
["A woman has faced\u00a0a Sydney court after allegedly fleecing a Canberra woman out of $1 million.", "New South Wales cybercrime detectives arrested Annelise Sunderland, 29,\u00a0in November, and will allege she fraudulently took the money during a property settlement earlier this year.", "It is\u00a0alleged a woman in the ACT unwittingly deposited $1 million into a fraudulent account \u2014\u00a0the details of which\u00a0had been taken from a compromised email sent to the buyer's lawyer.\u00a0", "Today, Ms Sunderland faced Parramatta local court where she pleaded not guilty to two counts of recklessly dealing with the proceeds of crime.\u00a0", "", "
Annelise Sunderland leaves Parramatta Local Court after pleading not guilty to allegedly defrauding a Canberra woman of $1 million.\u00a0(ABC News: Tony Ibrahim)
", "
Police urge online caution
", "Ms Sunderland's arrest came several months after cybercrime police set up Strike Force Urban to investigate \"invoice frauds\" and \"business email compromise\" scams.\u00a0", "These types\u00a0of fraud involve the creation of a fake invoice\u00a0that contains account\u00a0details and requests money from an unsuspecting victim.\u00a0", "NSW Police said detectives were notified earlier this year\u00a0of an ACT woman depositing $1 million in a fraudulent account, during the settlement period of a property.", "During this period a buyer pays the remainder of a sale price and becomes the legal owner of a property.", "In October, detectives raided a unit in Parramatta and allegedly seized numerous mobile phones and documents for forensic analysis.\u00a0", "Today, Ms Sunderland faced Parramatta Local Court, where she entered not guilty pleas to her charges.\u00a0", "Ms Sunderland was released on bail and will face court again in February.\u00a0", "NSW Cybercrime Squad Commander Detective Superintendent Matthew Craft\u00a0said people must remain vigilant when conducting transactions online.", "\"Get in the habit of checking the email address, URL, and spelling used in all correspondence and heavily scrutinise all transactions that you make online,\" he said.", "\"To avoid being scammed, people should use two-step verification methods where appropriate, and regularly update and maintain strong passwords.\""]
